</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Computed tomography (CT) is key to the assessment of hemodynamically stable patients with blunt or penetrating trauma to the abdomen and pelvis. Dual-energy (DE) CT is a technology that allows acquisition of data at both high and low kilovolt peaks, allowing materials that have different x-ray absorption behaviors as a function of kilovolt peak (such as iodine) to be differentiated and quantified. DE CT has a variety of postprocessing applications that may be helpful in abdominal and pelvic trauma, including iodine-selective imaging, virtual monenergetic imaging, and virtual noncalcium imaging. Both iodine-selective imaging and virtual monoenergetic imaging can increase the conspicuity of traumatic solid-organ and hollow visceral injuries, making injuries easier to detect and categorize. Iodine-selective imaging, through the use of iodine maps and virtual noncontrast images, can assist in the evaluation of active contrast extravasation. Virtual noncalcium images can unmask bone marrow edema, improving detection of subtle fractures. The purpose of this review article is to familiarize radiologists with the basic physics and technical principles of DE CT, common postprocessing techniques, and the potential added value of DE CT in patients with abdominal and pelvic trauma. The technical limitations of DE CT are also reviewed, as are diagnostic pitfalls and common challenges in interpretation.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2018</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2018170058">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2018170058">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig1a.jpeg" height="1344" width="1799" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span>. Liver laceration and hematoma in a 20-year-old man who sustained blunt trauma. <b>(a)</b> Axial DE CT “mixed” image is a combination of low– and high–kilovolt peak images and simulates a traditional 120-kVp image. This can be decomposed into a VNC image with iodine subtraction <b>(b)</b> and an iodine overlay image <b>(c)</b> with the iodine content color coded (orange in <b>c</b>) and superimposed on the VNC image.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig1b.jpeg" height="1334" width="1771" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span>. Liver laceration and hematoma in a 20-year-old man who sustained blunt trauma. <b>(a)</b> Axial DE CT “mixed” image is a combination of low– and high–kilovolt peak images and simulates a traditional 120-kVp image. This can be decomposed into a VNC image with iodine subtraction <b>(b)</b> and an iodine overlay image <b>(c)</b> with the iodine content color coded (orange in <b>c</b>) and superimposed on the VNC image.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig1c.jpeg" height="1334" width="1779" aria-labelledby="fig1c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1c</span>. Liver laceration and hematoma in a 20-year-old man who sustained blunt trauma. <b>(a)</b> Axial DE CT “mixed” image is a combination of low– and high–kilovolt peak images and simulates a traditional 120-kVp image. This can be decomposed into a VNC image with iodine subtraction <b>(b)</b> and an iodine overlay image <b>(c)</b> with the iodine content color coded (orange in <b>c</b>) and superimposed on the VNC image.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig1c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig2a.jpeg" height="1392" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span>. Nondisplaced intertrochanter fracture in a 66-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Coronal mixed image shows subtle signs of fracture (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal virtual noncalcium image with calcified trabeculae removed shows underlying bone marrow edema color coded in green and fracture extension into the intertrochanteric region (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Coronal short inversion time inversion-recovery magnetic resonance (MR) image shows the same bone marrow edema as in <b>b</b> (arrow). (Case courtesy of Bharti Khurana, MD, Brigham and Women’s Hospital, Boston, Mass.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig2b.jpeg" height="1519" width="1545" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span>. Nondisplaced intertrochanter fracture in a 66-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Coronal mixed image shows subtle signs of fracture (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal virtual noncalcium image with calcified trabeculae removed shows underlying bone marrow edema color coded in green and fracture extension into the intertrochanteric region (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Coronal short inversion time inversion-recovery magnetic resonance (MR) image shows the same bone marrow edema as in <b>b</b> (arrow). (Case courtesy of Bharti Khurana, MD, Brigham and Women’s Hospital, Boston, Mass.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig2c.jpeg" height="1518" width="1604" aria-labelledby="fig2c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2c</span>. Nondisplaced intertrochanter fracture in a 66-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Coronal mixed image shows subtle signs of fracture (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal virtual noncalcium image with calcified trabeculae removed shows underlying bone marrow edema color coded in green and fracture extension into the intertrochanteric region (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Coronal short inversion time inversion-recovery magnetic resonance (MR) image shows the same bone marrow edema as in <b>b</b> (arrow). (Case courtesy of Bharti Khurana, MD, Brigham and Women’s Hospital, Boston, Mass.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig2c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig3a.jpeg" height="1396" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. Liver injury in a 24-year-old man who sustained blunt trauma. <b>(a)</b> Axial DE CT mixed image shows injury in the right hepatic lobe. Virtual monoenergetic images simulate the expected image appearance if the images were obtained by using a single kiloelectron volt level. <b>(b)</b> Axial 40-keV image shows increased conspicuity of iodine content in vessels and structures. <b>(c)</b> Axial 70-keV image shows a rough approximation of the appearance of a 120-kVp image, or the DE CT mixed image. <b>(d, e)</b> Axial 100-keV <b>(d)</b> and 130-keV <b>(e)</b> images show that the conspicuity of the iodine content decreases with increasing kiloelectron volt levels.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig3b.jpeg" height="1379" width="1579" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. Liver injury in a 24-year-old man who sustained blunt trauma. <b>(a)</b> Axial DE CT mixed image shows injury in the right hepatic lobe. Virtual monoenergetic images simulate the expected image appearance if the images were obtained by using a single kiloelectron volt level. <b>(b)</b> Axial 40-keV image shows increased conspicuity of iodine content in vessels and structures. <b>(c)</b> Axial 70-keV image shows a rough approximation of the appearance of a 120-kVp image, or the DE CT mixed image. <b>(d, e)</b> Axial 100-keV <b>(d)</b> and 130-keV <b>(e)</b> images show that the conspicuity of the iodine content decreases with increasing kiloelectron volt levels.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig3c.jpeg" height="1378" width="1570" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span>. Liver injury in a 24-year-old man who sustained blunt trauma. <b>(a)</b> Axial DE CT mixed image shows injury in the right hepatic lobe. Virtual monoenergetic images simulate the expected image appearance if the images were obtained by using a single kiloelectron volt level. <b>(b)</b> Axial 40-keV image shows increased conspicuity of iodine content in vessels and structures. <b>(c)</b> Axial 70-keV image shows a rough approximation of the appearance of a 120-kVp image, or the DE CT mixed image. <b>(d, e)</b> Axial 100-keV <b>(d)</b> and 130-keV <b>(e)</b> images show that the conspicuity of the iodine content decreases with increasing kiloelectron volt levels.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig3d.jpeg" height="1377" width="1561" aria-labelledby="fig3d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3d</span>. Liver injury in a 24-year-old man who sustained blunt trauma. <b>(a)</b> Axial DE CT mixed image shows injury in the right hepatic lobe. Virtual monoenergetic images simulate the expected image appearance if the images were obtained by using a single kiloelectron volt level. <b>(b)</b> Axial 40-keV image shows increased conspicuity of iodine content in vessels and structures. <b>(c)</b> Axial 70-keV image shows a rough approximation of the appearance of a 120-kVp image, or the DE CT mixed image. <b>(d, e)</b> Axial 100-keV <b>(d)</b> and 130-keV <b>(e)</b> images show that the conspicuity of the iodine content decreases with increasing kiloelectron volt levels.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig3d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig3e.jpeg" height="1378" width="1588" aria-labelledby="fig3e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3e</span>. Liver injury in a 24-year-old man who sustained blunt trauma. <b>(a)</b> Axial DE CT mixed image shows injury in the right hepatic lobe. Virtual monoenergetic images simulate the expected image appearance if the images were obtained by using a single kiloelectron volt level. <b>(b)</b> Axial 40-keV image shows increased conspicuity of iodine content in vessels and structures. <b>(c)</b> Axial 70-keV image shows a rough approximation of the appearance of a 120-kVp image, or the DE CT mixed image. <b>(d, e)</b> Axial 100-keV <b>(d)</b> and 130-keV <b>(e)</b> images show that the conspicuity of the iodine content decreases with increasing kiloelectron volt levels.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig3e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig4a.jpeg" height="1892" width="1221" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Injuries in a 31-year-old woman who fell from a ladder. <b>(a)</b> Coronal mixed image shows multiple right renal lacerations and a small amount of perinephric hemorrhage. <b>(b)</b> Coronal iodine overlay image shows better-visualized lacerations, particularly in the lower pole of the right kidney.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig4b.jpeg" height="1891" width="1229" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Injuries in a 31-year-old woman who fell from a ladder. <b>(a)</b> Coronal mixed image shows multiple right renal lacerations and a small amount of perinephric hemorrhage. <b>(b)</b> Coronal iodine overlay image shows better-visualized lacerations, particularly in the lower pole of the right kidney.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig5a.jpeg" height="1514" width="1329" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. Splenic injury in a 66-year-old woman who sustained blunt trauma. <b>(a)</b> DE CT mixed image shows heterogeneity of the splenic parenchyma and a likely subcapsular hematoma. <b>(b)</b> Monoenergetic 45-keV image shows accentuated enhancement differences between the hematoma and the splenic parenchyma and also highlights a hypoattenuating laceration in the parenchyma (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig5b.jpeg" height="1517" width="1322" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. Splenic injury in a 66-year-old woman who sustained blunt trauma. <b>(a)</b> DE CT mixed image shows heterogeneity of the splenic parenchyma and a likely subcapsular hematoma. <b>(b)</b> Monoenergetic 45-keV image shows accentuated enhancement differences between the hematoma and the splenic parenchyma and also highlights a hypoattenuating laceration in the parenchyma (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig6a.jpeg" height="1392" width="1240" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. Injury in a 25-year-old woman after a motor vehicle collision. <b>(a)</b> Axial DE CT mixed image shows an area of injury with an internal focus of high attenuation in the right lobe of the liver (arrow in <b>a</b>–<b>c</b>) that could represent active extravasation or parenchymal hematoma. <b>(b, c)</b> This area is hyperattenuating on an axial VNC image <b>(b)</b> and contains no iodine content on an iodine overlay image <b>(c)</b>, which confirms that it represents a hematoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig6b.jpeg" height="1392" width="1240" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. Injury in a 25-year-old woman after a motor vehicle collision. <b>(a)</b> Axial DE CT mixed image shows an area of injury with an internal focus of high attenuation in the right lobe of the liver (arrow in <b>a</b>–<b>c</b>) that could represent active extravasation or parenchymal hematoma. <b>(b, c)</b> This area is hyperattenuating on an axial VNC image <b>(b)</b> and contains no iodine content on an iodine overlay image <b>(c)</b>, which confirms that it represents a hematoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig6c.jpeg" height="1393" width="1220" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span>. Injury in a 25-year-old woman after a motor vehicle collision. <b>(a)</b> Axial DE CT mixed image shows an area of injury with an internal focus of high attenuation in the right lobe of the liver (arrow in <b>a</b>–<b>c</b>) that could represent active extravasation or parenchymal hematoma. <b>(b, c)</b> This area is hyperattenuating on an axial VNC image <b>(b)</b> and contains no iodine content on an iodine overlay image <b>(c)</b>, which confirms that it represents a hematoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig7a.jpeg" height="1475" width="1576" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Bowel injury in a 23-year-old male pedestrian who was struck by a car. <b>(a)</b> Coronal mixed image shows multiple bowel loops in the left abdomen that are thickened and appear to be nonenhancing (arrows), with an adjacent loop that appears to be hyperenhancing. <b>(b)</b> Coronal iodine overlay image shows complete lack of iodine content in the bowel loop in the left abdomen (arrows). At laparotomy, multiple bowel loops showed signs of infarction due to serosal avulsion and were subsequently resected.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig7b.jpeg" height="1475" width="1574" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Bowel injury in a 23-year-old male pedestrian who was struck by a car. <b>(a)</b> Coronal mixed image shows multiple bowel loops in the left abdomen that are thickened and appear to be nonenhancing (arrows), with an adjacent loop that appears to be hyperenhancing. <b>(b)</b> Coronal iodine overlay image shows complete lack of iodine content in the bowel loop in the left abdomen (arrows). At laparotomy, multiple bowel loops showed signs of infarction due to serosal avulsion and were subsequently resected.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig8a.jpeg" height="1473" width="1232" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. Pelvic fractures and blood loss in the field in a 58-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Mixed DE CT image shows hyperattenuation in the bowel mucosa that could represent shock bowel, hemorrhage, or hyperattenuating ingested material. <b>(b, c)</b> This was confirmed to represent enhancement on the iodine overlay image <b>(b)</b> and the 45-keV monoenergetic image <b>(c)</b>, and was not present on VNC images (not shown). Additional findings of hypoperfusion complex are present, including inferior vena cava flattening and hyperenhancement of the kidneys.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig8b.jpeg" height="1473" width="1230" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. Pelvic fractures and blood loss in the field in a 58-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Mixed DE CT image shows hyperattenuation in the bowel mucosa that could represent shock bowel, hemorrhage, or hyperattenuating ingested material. <b>(b, c)</b> This was confirmed to represent enhancement on the iodine overlay image <b>(b)</b> and the 45-keV monoenergetic image <b>(c)</b>, and was not present on VNC images (not shown). Additional findings of hypoperfusion complex are present, including inferior vena cava flattening and hyperenhancement of the kidneys.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig8c.jpeg" height="1473" width="1239" aria-labelledby="fig8c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8c</span>. Pelvic fractures and blood loss in the field in a 58-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Mixed DE CT image shows hyperattenuation in the bowel mucosa that could represent shock bowel, hemorrhage, or hyperattenuating ingested material. <b>(b, c)</b> This was confirmed to represent enhancement on the iodine overlay image <b>(b)</b> and the 45-keV monoenergetic image <b>(c)</b>, and was not present on VNC images (not shown). Additional findings of hypoperfusion complex are present, including inferior vena cava flattening and hyperenhancement of the kidneys.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig8c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig9a.jpeg" height="1502" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Acetabular fracture in a 44-year-old man who sustained blunt trauma. DE CT mixed image <b>(a)</b> shows a high-attenuating focus (red arrow) adjacent to the fracture that is not present on the VNC image <b>(b)</b> and is present on the iodine overlay image <b>(c)</b>, which is diagnostic of a site of active extravasation. Adjacent to this, there are additional high-attenuation foci that are present in both <b>b</b> and <b>c</b> and are consistent with bone fragments (yellow arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig9b.jpeg" height="1469" width="1476" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Acetabular fracture in a 44-year-old man who sustained blunt trauma. DE CT mixed image <b>(a)</b> shows a high-attenuating focus (red arrow) adjacent to the fracture that is not present on the VNC image <b>(b)</b> and is present on the iodine overlay image <b>(c)</b>, which is diagnostic of a site of active extravasation. Adjacent to this, there are additional high-attenuation foci that are present in both <b>b</b> and <b>c</b> and are consistent with bone fragments (yellow arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig9c.jpeg" height="1469" width="1474" aria-labelledby="fig9c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span>. Acetabular fracture in a 44-year-old man who sustained blunt trauma. DE CT mixed image <b>(a)</b> shows a high-attenuating focus (red arrow) adjacent to the fracture that is not present on the VNC image <b>(b)</b> and is present on the iodine overlay image <b>(c)</b>, which is diagnostic of a site of active extravasation. Adjacent to this, there are additional high-attenuation foci that are present in both <b>b</b> and <b>c</b> and are consistent with bone fragments (yellow arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig9c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig10a.jpeg" height="1556" width="1330" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. Gunshot wound to the left thigh in a 21-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> DE CT mixed image shows multiple high-attenuation foci (arrows) adjacent to the left iliac bone that could represent sites of active extravasation or bone fragments. <b>(b)</b> VNC image shows that these foci remain present (arrows), which confirms that they are bone fragments from ballistic injury to the iliac bone and not foci of active extravasation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig10b.jpeg" height="1556" width="1320" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. Gunshot wound to the left thigh in a 21-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> DE CT mixed image shows multiple high-attenuation foci (arrows) adjacent to the left iliac bone that could represent sites of active extravasation or bone fragments. <b>(b)</b> VNC image shows that these foci remain present (arrows), which confirms that they are bone fragments from ballistic injury to the iliac bone and not foci of active extravasation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig11a.jpeg" height="1723" width="1109" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figures 11a</span>. Adrenal hematoma in a 53-year-old man who fell down multiple stairs. <b>(11a)</b> DE CT mixed image shows heterogeneous high attenuation surrounding the right adrenal gland (arrow). <b>(11b)</b> VNC image shows that this material is all intrinsically hyperattenuating (arrow). <b>(11c)</b> Iodine overlay image shows no iodine content (arrow), consistent with an adrenal hematoma without active extravasation of contrast material.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig11b.jpeg" height="1723" width="1093" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figures 11b</span>. Adrenal hematoma in a 53-year-old man who fell down multiple stairs. <b>(11a)</b> DE CT mixed image shows heterogeneous high attenuation surrounding the right adrenal gland (arrow). <b>(11b)</b> VNC image shows that this material is all intrinsically hyperattenuating (arrow). <b>(11c)</b> Iodine overlay image shows no iodine content (arrow), consistent with an adrenal hematoma without active extravasation of contrast material.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig11c.jpeg" height="1723" width="1096" aria-labelledby="fig11c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figures 11c</span>. Adrenal hematoma in a 53-year-old man who fell down multiple stairs. <b>(11a)</b> DE CT mixed image shows heterogeneous high attenuation surrounding the right adrenal gland (arrow). <b>(11b)</b> VNC image shows that this material is all intrinsically hyperattenuating (arrow). <b>(11c)</b> Iodine overlay image shows no iodine content (arrow), consistent with an adrenal hematoma without active extravasation of contrast material.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig11c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig12a.jpeg" height="1522" width="1222" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figures 12a</span>. Active extravasation in a 55-year-old woman after a motor vehicle collision who later underwent emergency laparotomy. <b>(12a)</b> DE CT mixed image shows stranding and hematoma in the omental fat adjacent to the stomach, with a focus of high attenuation (arrow). <b>(12b)</b> VNC image does not show the focus that appears in <b>a</b>. <b>(12c)</b> Iodine overlay image shows iodine content (arrow), confirming that it represents active extravasation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig12b.jpeg" height="1522" width="1237" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figures 12b</span>. Active extravasation in a 55-year-old woman after a motor vehicle collision who later underwent emergency laparotomy. <b>(12a)</b> DE CT mixed image shows stranding and hematoma in the omental fat adjacent to the stomach, with a focus of high attenuation (arrow). <b>(12b)</b> VNC image does not show the focus that appears in <b>a</b>. <b>(12c)</b> Iodine overlay image shows iodine content (arrow), confirming that it represents active extravasation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig12c.jpeg" height="1522" width="1240" aria-labelledby="fig12c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figures 12c</span>. Active extravasation in a 55-year-old woman after a motor vehicle collision who later underwent emergency laparotomy. <b>(12a)</b> DE CT mixed image shows stranding and hematoma in the omental fat adjacent to the stomach, with a focus of high attenuation (arrow). <b>(12b)</b> VNC image does not show the focus that appears in <b>a</b>. <b>(12c)</b> Iodine overlay image shows iodine content (arrow), confirming that it represents active extravasation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig12c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig13a.jpeg" height="1006" width="1671" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. Fracture in a 78-year-old woman after a fall. <b>(a)</b> Coronal mixed image shows a subtle linear lucency in the right acetabulum (arrow), which correlated with the site of the patient’s pain. <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal <b>(b)</b> and axial <b>(c)</b> virtual noncalcium images show asymmetric bone marrow edema (arrow, edema color coded in green) in the right superior pubic ramus and acetabulum, which suggests a nondisplaced fracture. <b>(d)</b> Thin-section axial bone reconstruction image shows a subtle nondisplaced fracture (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig13b.jpeg" height="1043" width="1422" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. Fracture in a 78-year-old woman after a fall. <b>(a)</b> Coronal mixed image shows a subtle linear lucency in the right acetabulum (arrow), which correlated with the site of the patient’s pain. <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal <b>(b)</b> and axial <b>(c)</b> virtual noncalcium images show asymmetric bone marrow edema (arrow, edema color coded in green) in the right superior pubic ramus and acetabulum, which suggests a nondisplaced fracture. <b>(d)</b> Thin-section axial bone reconstruction image shows a subtle nondisplaced fracture (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig13c.jpeg" height="1006" width="2079" aria-labelledby="fig13c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13c</span>. Fracture in a 78-year-old woman after a fall. <b>(a)</b> Coronal mixed image shows a subtle linear lucency in the right acetabulum (arrow), which correlated with the site of the patient’s pain. <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal <b>(b)</b> and axial <b>(c)</b> virtual noncalcium images show asymmetric bone marrow edema (arrow, edema color coded in green) in the right superior pubic ramus and acetabulum, which suggests a nondisplaced fracture. <b>(d)</b> Thin-section axial bone reconstruction image shows a subtle nondisplaced fracture (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig13c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig13d.jpeg" height="1041" width="1230" aria-labelledby="fig13d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13d</span>. Fracture in a 78-year-old woman after a fall. <b>(a)</b> Coronal mixed image shows a subtle linear lucency in the right acetabulum (arrow), which correlated with the site of the patient’s pain. <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal <b>(b)</b> and axial <b>(c)</b> virtual noncalcium images show asymmetric bone marrow edema (arrow, edema color coded in green) in the right superior pubic ramus and acetabulum, which suggests a nondisplaced fracture. <b>(d)</b> Thin-section axial bone reconstruction image shows a subtle nondisplaced fracture (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig13d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig14a.jpeg" height="1044" width="1674" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. Lipid-rich adrenal adenoma in an 89-year-old man who sustained blunt trauma. <b>(a)</b> Axial DE CT mixed image shows an indeterminate right adrenal mass with attenuation of 40 HU. <b>(b)</b> Axial VNC image shows the mass with attenuation of 9 HU.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170058/asset/images/large/rg.2018170058.fig14b.jpeg" height="1044" width="1677" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span>. Lipid-rich adrenal adenoma in an 89-year-old man who sustained blunt trauma. <b>(a)</b> Axial DE CT mixed image shows an indeterminate right adrenal mass with attenuation of 40 HU. <b>(b)</b> Axial VNC image shows the mass with attenuation of 9 HU.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170058&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Romano L, Giovine S, Guidi G, Tortora G, Cinque T, Romano S. Hepatic trauma: CT findings and considerations based on our experience in emergency diagnostic imaging. <em>Eur J Radiol</em> 2004;50(1):59–66.</div><